Higher value, lower quality (0 = best quality, 16 = worst quality; default value is 1). Note: this is linked with "texture detail" option in "graphics" menu, and the lowest quality you can set from there corresponds to r_picmip 3, thus altough you manually set it to an high value (for example, 8), when you will change anything from

:SooKee!~SooKee@SooKee.users.quakenet.org PRIVMSG #openarenahelp :<`gb`> can you tell me how to disable mouse acceleration in OA running on ubuntu or other linux?
:SooKee!~SooKee@SooKee.users.quakenet.org PRIVMSG #openarenahelp :yes, 
:SooKee!~SooKee@SooKee.users.quakenet.org PRIVMSG #openarenahelp :xset m 1/1 1
:SooKee!~SooKee@SooKee.users.quakenet.org PRIVMSG #openarenahelp :try man xset
:SooKee!~SooKee@SooKee.users.quakenet.org PRIVMSG #openarenahelp :you can put that in a script to launch OA 
:SooKee!~SooKee@SooKee.users.quakenet.org PRIVMSG #openarenahelp :==== Incoming flood!! ====
:SooKee!~SooKee@SooKee.users.quakenet.org PRIVMSG #openarenahelp :# Record mouse accel
:SooKee!~SooKee@SooKee.users.quakenet.org PRIVMSG #openarenahelp :ACCELERATION=$(xset q|grep acceleration:|cut -d " " -f 5)
:SooKee!~SooKee@SooKee.users.quakenet.org PRIVMSG #openarenahelp :THRESHOLD=$(xset q|grep acceleration:|cut -d " " -f 11)
:SooKee!~SooKee@SooKee.users.quakenet.org PRIVMSG #openarenahelp :## Turn off acceleration 
:SooKee!~SooKee@SooKee.users.quakenet.org PRIVMSG #openarenahelp :xset m 1/1 1
:SooKee!~SooKee@SooKee.users.quakenet.org PRIVMSG #openarenahelp :openarena
:SooKee!~SooKee@SooKee.users.quakenet.org PRIVMSG #openarenahelp :# Restore mouse accel
:SooKee!~SooKee@SooKee.users.quakenet.org PRIVMSG #openarenahelp :xset m $ACCELERATION $THRESHOLD

:SooKee!~SooKee@SooKee.users.quakenet.org PRIVMSG #openarenahelp :`gb`, are you using cl_timenudge ?
:SooKee!~SooKee@SooKee.users.quakenet.org PRIVMSG #openarenahelp :Setting cl_timenudge to a positive value adds a delay of that number of milliseconds to the game controls (e.g. mouse and keyboard), but subtracts that same number of milliseconds from the lag on your display. You experience no lag on your display, but at the expense of doubling the lag on your game controls.

:Pixelized!~Who@dsl-216-221-61-50.mtl.aei.ca PRIVMSG #openarenahelp :if all patches on a network as 568-A one should use all 568-A patch cabling
:Pixelized!~Who@dsl-216-221-61-50.mtl.aei.ca PRIVMSG #openarenahelp :and vice versa
:Pixelized!~Who@dsl-216-221-61-50.mtl.aei.ca PRIVMSG #openarenahelp :techinically if you are using a crossover on a 568-A network the 568-B end should go in the device and 568-A end in the network
:Pixelized!~Who@dsl-216-221-61-50.mtl.aei.ca PRIVMSG #openarenahelp :RMF: to answer your previous question
:Pixelized!~Who@dsl-216-221-61-50.mtl.aei.ca PRIVMSG #openarenahelp :RMF: CAT5 is 24AWG wiring and CAT6 is 22AWG...as for the twist ratio
:Pixelized!~Who@dsl-216-221-61-50.mtl.aei.ca PRIVMSG #openarenahelp :thus why cat6 doesn't terminate well in cat5 RJ45 heads
:Pixelized!~Who@dsl-216-221-61-50.mtl.aei.ca PRIVMSG #openarenahelp :RMF: the twisted pair scenario is to cancel out EMI

:RMF!~luc@a83-161-210-237.adsl.xs4all.nl PRIVMSG #openarenahelp :AWG*
:Pixelized!~Who@dsl-216-221-61-50.mtl.aei.ca PRIVMSG #openarenahelp :and crosstalk between the pairs themselves
:Pixelized!~Who@dsl-216-221-61-50.mtl.aei.ca PRIVMSG #openarenahelp :American Wire Gauge
:Pixelized!~Who@dsl-216-221-61-50.mtl.aei.ca PRIVMSG #openarenahelp :size of wire =)
